NEF Northbound APIs
5.1 Introduction

The NEF Northbound Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) constitute a standardized set of interfaces defining the operational procedures and resource models that facilitate bidirectional interaction between the Network Exposure Function (NEF) and the Application Function (AF). These APIs serve a pivotal role in enabling external applications to securely and efficiently access network capabilities, orchestrate service communication patterns, and influence data flows within both Evolved Packet System (EPS) and 5G System (5GS) environments.
5.2 Information Applicable to Several APIs

The NEF Northbound APIs adhere to the conventions of the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) for communication and define content formats consistent with the specifications in subclauses 5.2.2 and 5.2.3 of 3GPP TS 29.122. Consequently, HTTP serves as the transport mechanism upon which service visibility, resource manipulation, and state synchronization depend.

Furthermore, key operational mechanisms including notification handling, error management, feature negotiation, and HTTP custom header utilization are governed by the rules defined in subclauses 5.2.5 through 5.2.8 of 3GPP TS 29.122. However, in this specification, the SCEF (Service Capability Exposure Function) has been superseded by the NEF, and the SCS/AS has been replaced by the AF to reflect the architecture of the 5GS service exposure framework.

Similarly, the conventions guiding the OpenAPI specification files, as set forth in subclause 5.2.10 of 3GPP TS 29.122, are fully applicable to the NEF Northbound APIs to ensure alignment with industry standards and facilitate interoperability across vendors.
